e focusing on the work of five contemporary Asian American poets-Li-Young Lee, Marilyn Chin, John Yau, Mei-mei Berssenbrugge, and Pamela Lu-the book contends that aesthetic forms are inseparable from social, political, and historical contexts in the writing and reception of all poetry. Wang questions the tendency of critics and academics alike to occlude the role of race in their discussions of the American poetic tradition and casts a harsh light on the double standard they apply in reading poems by poets who are racial minorities. This is the first sustained study of the formal properties in Asian American poetry across a range of aesthetic styles, from traditional lyric to avant-garde. Wang argues with conviction that critics should read minority poetry with the same attention to language and form that they bring to their analyses of writing by white poets.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAmerican poetryxAsian American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican poetryxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aLiterary form. 0aPoetics. 4aAsian American. 4aJohn Yau. 4aLi-Young Lee. 4aMarilyn Chin. 4aMei-mei Berssenbrugge. 4aPamela Lu. 4acultural studies. 4aliterary history. 4apoetry. 4arace studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Asian American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804789097zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804789097423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804789097.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles